hs\"]}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"11,600\"}],[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"children\":\"Nicknames\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"Sofi, Fifi\"}]]]}]]}]\n1b:[\"$\",\"article\",\"Eliana\",{\"className\":\"spotlight-card\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"span\",null,{\"className\":\"spotlight-rank\",\"children\":[\"#\",10]}],[\"$\",\"h3\",null,{\"children\":\"Eliana\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"className\":\"pronounce\",\"children\":[\"/\",\"el-ee-AH-nuh\",\"/\"]}],[\"$\",\"dl\",null,{\"className\":\"spotlight-facts\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"children\":\"Meaning\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"God has answered\"}],[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"children\":\"Origin\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"Hebrew\"}],[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"children\":[2025,\" Births\"]}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"11,300\"}],[[\"$\",\"dt\",null,{\"children\":\"Nicknames\"}],[\"$\",\"dd\",null,{\"children\":\"Ellie, Ana, Ani\"}]]]}]]}]\n1d:[\"$\",\"details\",\"How many babies does the top 100 list actually represent?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"How many babies does the top 100 list actually represent?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"The top 100 boy names cover 128,000 births and the top 100 girl names cover 119,000 births in 2025 — together representing just over 1.15 million of the roughly 3.6 million Social Security card applications filed for newborns that year.\"}]]}]\n1e:[\"$\",\"details\",\"What's a 'combined' top 100 baby names list?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"What's a 'combined' top 100 baby names list?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"Since the SSA ranks boys' and girls' names separately (each with its own top 1000), a single 'Top 100 Baby Names' list is usually built by combining the top 50 boy names and top 50 girl names into one table, which is the format used on this page.\"}]]}]\n1f:[\"$\",\"details\",\"Will next year's list look very different?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"Will next year's list look very different?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"Usually not at the very top — the top 4–5 names in each gender tend to be stable year over year. Most of the real movement happens between roughly rank 20 and rank 100, where names can rise or fall by 10+ spots in a single year.\"}]]}]\n20:[\"$\",\"details\",\"Is a name 'popular' the same as a name 'trending'?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"Is a name 'popular' the same as a name 'trending'?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"Not quite. Popular usually means high total volume (like Liam or Olivia, which have topped the list for years). Trending refers to year-over-year movement — a name like Cooper or Eloise can be trending up fast while still ranking outside the top 20 overall.\"}]]}]\n21:[\"$\",\"details\",\"Where can I see the full top 1,000 names, not just the top 100?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"Where can I see the full top 1,000 names, not just the top 100?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"The Social Security Administration publishes the complete top 1,000 names per gender, per year, along with historical data back to 1880, at ssa.gov/oact/babynames.\"}]]}]\n22:[\"$\",\"details\",\"Do unisex or gender-neutral names appear on this list?\",{\"className\":\"faq-item\",\"children\":[[\"$\",\"summary\",null,{\"children\":\"Do unisex or gender-neutral names appear on this list?\"}],[\"$\",\"p\",null,{\"children\":\"The SSA tracks name counts separately by the sex recorded on each Social Security application, so a name like Riley appears once in the boys' list and once in the girls' list with two different ranks and birth counts, rather than as a single unisex entry.\"}]]}]\n","/top-baby-names-usa":"1:\"$Sreact.fragment\"\n2:I[39756,[\"/_next/static/chunks/01xlw8hd842-c.js\",\"/_next/sta